    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3396618428" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3396618428" />
    <a title="jade" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/11030012-jade"><img alt="jade" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1562419355p2/11030012.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3396618428?book_show_action=true">Jun 22, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="jade" class="user" itemprop="url" name="jade" href="/user/show/11030012-jade">jade</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback " href="/book/show/21074405-five-little-pigs">review of another edition</a>

          <div><span class="uitext greyText">Recommends it for: </span>
           <span class="uitext reviewText">murder mystery fans who like quieter, melancholy family tragedies of past years</span></div>

          <div>
    <span class="greyText">Recommended to jade by: </span>
      <a href="/user/show/107881343-library-girl-reading">library girl reading</a>
  </div>


          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/11030012-jade?shelf=murder-mysteries">murder-mysteries</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/11030012-jade?shelf=buddy-reads">buddy-reads</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3396618428" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13209850882904704380"><blockquote>
  <b>
    <i>“what do most people mean when they say that? so young. something innocent, something appealing, something helpless. but youth is not that! youth is crude, youth is strong, youth is powerful — yes, and cruel! and one thing more — youth is vulnerable.”</i>
  </b>
</blockquote><br/>sixteen years ago, caroline crale poisoned her temperamental husband amyas and was convicted of the crime. armed with a letter written by her mother and a wish to lay all doubts to rest, caroline’s daughter now wants to reopen the case a</span>
  <span id="freeText13209850882904704380" style="display:none"><blockquote>
  <b>
    <i>“what do most people mean when they say that? so young. something innocent, something appealing, something helpless. but youth is not that! youth is crude, youth is strong, youth is powerful — yes, and cruel! and one thing more — youth is vulnerable.”</i>
  </b>
</blockquote><br />sixteen years ago, caroline crale poisoned her temperamental husband amyas and was convicted of the crime. armed with a letter written by her mother and a wish to lay all doubts to rest, caroline’s daughter now wants to reopen the case and figure out the real truth of it.<br /><br />she of course hires everybody’s favorite belgian detective for the job: <b>hercule poirot.</b><br /><br />and he puts his little grey cells to work, dredging up tragedy, complex relationships, and false assumptions. he talks with all the officials involved in the case -- lawyers, prosecutors, superintendents -- before moving onto the titular five little pigs.<br /><br />they represent the five witnesses of the case: <b>philip blake</b>, a stockbroker and amyas crale’s best friend; <b>meredith blake</b>, philip’s brother and a close friend of caroline crale’s; <b>elsa greer</b>, an ambitious, modern woman who was deeply in love with amyas; <b>angela warren</b>, caroline’s moody and mischievous teenage sister; and <b>miss williams</b>, angela’s utterly professional feminist governess.<br /><br />they all give <b>wildly different perspectives</b> on who caroline crale was and whether they consider her guilty or innocent. and poirot has to navigate the inaccuracies, bias, and little nuggets of truth hidden in their testimonies.<br /><br />i LOVED this book. honestly, ever since reading it i’ve been surprised that i’ve never really seen it pop up on lists with Best Poirot Novels. criminally underrated, if you ask me.<br /><br />it’s got <b>a melancholy nostalgia</b> to it that tugged at my heartstrings. as a reader, you slowly uncover the relationships between all the people in the book to a point where the story feels genuinely haunting. you can sense the intangible presence of both caroline and amyas, even so many years past, and while poirot’s investigation unfolds you get a feeling for how weirdly tangled up all these people were with each other.<br /><br />there’s <b>an incredibly poignant scene</b> during which meredith blake shows poirot the old house where the crales lived, and talks of how they all grew up together as childhood friends. how he and his brother would take their little boat and row over to caroline and amyas -- and you can tell how much it affects him. he’s torn and conflicted, as if he can still see them all having fun together, and wonders where that wonderful time went, marred by the murder and death of both his friends. that scene truly embodies the feeling of this story for me.<br /><br />the <b>structural presentation</b> of this book is also satisfyingly clean. chapters are divided per character, moving from interviews between them and poirot to the written narratives that they send to him afterwards. it <i>can</i> get <b>a little repetitive</b> because of that; you see the same events through five different perspectives, after all, so there’s bound to be overlap and repeat performances.<br /><br />but i loved how the whole book felt as if someone had handed me a bunch of casefiles and videotaped interviews. and it is definitely true that all five accounts feel and sound different in terms of narrative voice; it’s not just a matter of Spot The Conflicting Clue.<br /><br />poirot is also actually <b>a good character</b> in this. usually he just shows up with his quirky antics and arrogance, acting as a crime solving placeholder for the reader, but in this story he’s very much a human being. we see his sympathy for the people involved in the case, and how carefully he goes about manipulating the witnesses into giving him the answers he seeks.<br /><br />in conclusion, this was a very pleasant reading experience for me because i was very <b>emotionally involved</b> in the tragedy at the core of the story. i could empathize with almost every character, and the reveal plus underlying mystery were very well-executed (pardon the pun).<br /><br />if the characters and their familial tragedy are hard for you to connect to, though, this will likely be middle-of-the-road-poirot. but as a self-proclaimed sentimental fool, this story hit me <i>just right</i>.<br /><br />✎ <i>4.5 stars.</i></span>
  <a data-text-id="13209850882904704380" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


