<div id="review_1272197295" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1272197295" />
    <a title="Kavita" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5858699-kavita"><img alt="Kavita" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1315387023p2/5858699.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1272197295?book_show_action=true">May 05, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kavita" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kavita" href="/user/show/5858699-kavita">Kavita</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5858699-kavita?shelf=mystery">mystery</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5858699-kavita?shelf=uk">uk</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5858699-kavita?shelf=golden-age-mystery">golden-age-mystery</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1272197295" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11013221272523068251"><i>This little piggy went to market,<br/>This little piggy stayed home,<br/>This little piggy had roast beef<br/>This little piggy had none,<br/>And this little piggy cried wee wee wee all the way home.</i><br/><br/>Another nursery rhyme book! Poirot solves a cold case in this one. The daughter of a convicted murdereress, Carla Lemarchant, approaches him to find the truth behind the murder of her father. Poirot takes it only because of his passion for the truth, but it is not an easy journey. He interviews everyone connected with t</span>
  <span id="freeText11013221272523068251" style="display:none"><i>This little piggy went to market,<br />This little piggy stayed home,<br />This little piggy had roast beef<br />This little piggy had none,<br />And this little piggy cried wee wee wee all the way home.</i><br /><br />Another nursery rhyme book! Poirot solves a cold case in this one. The daughter of a convicted murdereress, Carla Lemarchant, approaches him to find the truth behind the murder of her father. Poirot takes it only because of his passion for the truth, but it is not an easy journey. He interviews everyone connected with the case - police officers and lawyers, as well as the people present at the Crales' house party at the time of his death. As always, it is the small things that are often overlooked by the majority of people that leads Poirot to the truth.<br /><br />Amyas and Caroline Crale are not very sympathetic people and I just disliked both of them. If left to myself, I would have just brushed my hands and said 'good riddance'. Amyas is a sexist womaniser, who goes around the place sleeping with whomever takes his fancy, but expects his wife to be still there when he returns to his senses and goes back to her. Caroline Crale, on the other hand, goes through life fighting and screaming over her husband's infidelity, but refuses to leave him, because 'love'. This is depicted as a passionate love between two people who enjoy bickering. Yeah, right! <br /><br />But murder is murder, and even the most unpleasant person deserves justice. So you feel motivated to follow Poirot's train of thought towards the inevitable end. <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[The clues in this book are pretty obvious, if only to prove Caroline's innocence. Poirot, of course, catches the real murderer and all ends well for Carla, who can now marry her lover without worrying about her past. <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br /><br />The other characters are very well-drawn and each had their own distinct way of looking at life. I enjoyed the book, especially since it clearly showed how (i) people see only what they want to see, (ii) people all give different versions of the same event, even if they are all speaking the truth, and (iii) everyone has something to hide. It's a great example of how a cold case can be solved and still retain the emotional and human elements that are of such interest to the mystery reader.</span>
  <a data-text-id="11013221272523068251" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


